title: For Sale:  Year 2000 German PPK
postcontent:
Walther PPK manufactured in the year 2000 (AA date code) from my private collection. I purchased this pistol from Earl’s Repair Service several years ago. This PPK was manufactured in ULM and has no import markings. It is unfired except for the factory testing. This gun is very unique in that not only is it a year 2000 PPK manufactured in Ulm but it also has a 5mm longer grip. According to Earl he received 30 of these PPK’s with the extended grip.
  However with this specific platform the PPK would meet all the requirements of the 1968 Gun Act which eliminated the import of the German made PPK pistols. S&W eventually got the contract and the PPK was manufactured in the U.S. from 2000 on. Regardless this is a very rare PPK, German made and German stamped. Comes with the original box, instruction booklet, test target, two magazines, the original receipt from Earls, and custom wooden grips.

title: For Sale:  Romanian AK47 SBR (7.62x39)
postcontent:
This rifle has been modified under the techniques pioneered and applied by Jim Fuller of Rifle Dynamics.  Most people will throw on some AR-style accessories and call it modern, but this fundamentally changed to turn it an AK that is up-to-date.  

The original 45-degree gas block has been replaced by a 90-degree Bolton Gas Block, which brings your sight post closer to the eye.  The barrel has been shortened by a to 14" and a Venom Tactical Muzzle Break has been pinned giving it the proper 16.5" length required by law; this alone changes the balance and weight distribution of the gun, making for tighter control.  The moving parts of the firearm have been worked and smoothed slowly over the period of a year. 

All work requiring gunsmithing was preformed by a professional in the Central Kentucky region.

Overall, the firearm will include:
- WASR-10 AK47 SBR, 7.62x39
- Bolton Gas Block with Sight Post
- Venom Tactical Muzzle Device (welded)
- Ultimak Gas Tube, vented
- Houge rubberized hand grip and foregrip
- Magpul AFG
- Widened rear sight leaf
- Romanian gas piston, pinned to the bolt carrier
- Tapco retainer plate
- 3 30rd Magazines
- Original wooden parts for rifle and hand grip
- Some type of sling

I never got around to getting a triangle folding stock for this, which would have been my last upgrade.  I also have a red dot I could throw in for $60.  

Overall this thing shoots better than any standard AK I've ever fired.  It has less recoil, better sights, and tighter control.  Unfortunately it does not double as a truck and that's ultimately what I need more in my life at the moment.  

Serious inquires only; research Jim and his work at RD if you're unsure what the effects are of having this type of work preformed to an AK-47 rifle.  

$1500, OBO.  Text or call REDACTED or reply via email from this ad.

The wood stock has a few minor dings, like every other SKS I've ever seen, and a hella lot less than most of them, it looks great.
  The receiver is machined steel, the barrel is threaded, with the short barrel lug. The serial number dates it as having a 1976 manufacture date, and all numbers are matching.
These run on the standard SKS 10-rd fixed magazine.

title: For Sale:  Kahr Pistols
postcontent:
I APOLOGIZE FOR THE LENGTH OF THIS POSTING BUT PLEASE READ ALL OF IT BEFORE RESPONDING.
I am a fan of Kahr pistols and have owned about twenty and currently have five.  I am offering three for sale, but I am only willing to sell two of them.  As soon as either one of the pocket sized .40 calibers sells, the other one returns to my safe.  I have several 9mm compact pistols, so I am going to sell this one.  The first gun in the picture is a CW9 9mm compact that is brand new.  The price is $380.  The second gun in the picture is a CM40 .40 caliber sub-compact that is also brand new.  The price is $400.  The third gun is a PM40 .40 caliber sub-compact that is blemish free, never been carried and shot only a handful of rounds.  They all have stainless slides, but the PM has a factory Black Diamond coating.  The two .40 caliber guns are the exact same size and all three are very slim at about 3/4" and weigh about 15-16 ounces.  The difference in the PM vs CM are as follows:   It has a molded plastic case, a polygonal rifled match barrel to increase the muzzle velocity in a 3" barrel to match those of a larger sized pistol.  It also comes with a spare magazine.  The PM model gets a dovetailed metal front sight and all square edges on the slide are machined smooth.  The frames and internals are the same on both guns.  Kahr just wanted to bring out a more affordable line to compete price wise with other manufacturers, so they added the "C" series since Kahr handguns are expensive.  All Kahrs have amazing triggers, polished feed ramps, stainless slide rails and are top shelf quality.  The price of the PM40 is $500.  ALL PRICES ARE FIRM.  I have them priced fairly and I am not willing to negotiate the prices.  I doubt I could make a trade as I have found the only way to successfully trade is to overprice my guns to allow for the unrealistic amounts people want for their trades and I didn't.  That means a trade that I take will also have to be priced right.  My PM40 retails for about $899.  I am also picky on what guns I own.  Every gun I have is new or like new in original box and I only have a handful of brands that I like.  I like Kahr, most Sigs, FNH, Springfields, most S&W, Ruger, Browning, Walther and Colt.  No long guns except maybe a Keltec KSG.  No 1911's.  I already have basically one of everything from Springfield.  POSSIBLE TRADES: A FNH FNS, a DA/SA Sig, a J frame S&W revolver, a Ruger GP101 .357, possibly a Browning or Walther and a very large DA revolver such as a Ruger .454 Casull, S&W .460 or .500, or possibly a .44 magnum.  I am in the Grassland area of Franklin and willing to meet at an agreed upon place in south Nashville, Brentwood, Franklin, Fairview, Spring Hill, or Thompson Station.  If you have a trade that might work, please send a picture and price.

title: For Sale:  VERY RARE Winchester Mod. 70 Pre 64 BULL GUN (Target)-3006 53*** serial number
postcontent: I have a very rare PRE 64 Bull Target rifle that is chambered in 3006 and sports a 28" barrel (very rare). This gun is in absolute perfect condition without a nick, dent, scratch or anything to any of the finish. Upon further review and deep research about this gun I have come to find (in table 4-22 of the rifleman’s rifle book) that this rifle is 1 of 844 EVER MADE!!! Winchester Model 70's in 3006 were the most common caliber of all created, but when it comes to the Bull Target there were very few ever created as the majority of Bull Targets were chambered in 300 H&H MAG. There were a total of 2,706 Bull Gun's made including 844 chambered in 3006 and 1,862 chambered in 300 H&H MAG so these guns are very rare and hard to find in this good of condition with a serial number in the low 50 thousands. This gun weighs a ton and will most likely be a bench shooter for the rest of its life. It has never been fired and has a perfect bore. I am in no rush to sell this gun as it is not taking up much space in my gun vault so please no low ball offers and i do not want to trade unless you have an Abram Tank. I have seen 1 rifle in as good of condition as this one but it was chambered in the 300 NOT in 3006 and it went for $11,000. I am asking 10,000 OBO, if you are serious contact me and we can work something out. Also i plenty more pics and can/will provide any information that you will need just let me know.
